# a)
*include an output of three rows*

```{r a}
wl_wide <- wl %>%
  filter(TREE_SPEC != 28 | is.na(TREE_SPEC)) %>%
  filter(FIELDNAME %in% c("DIAMETER", "HEIGHT", "DISTANCE", "NUM_STEMS")) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = c(SITECODE, SYEAR, TREEID, STEMID, TREE_SPEC),
    names_from = FIELDNAME,
    values_from = VALUE,
    values_fn = mean
  ) %>%
  select(SITECODE, SYEAR, TREE_SPEC, DIAMETER, HEIGHT, DISTANCE, NUM_STEMS)
head(wl_wide, 3)
```

# b)
*Limit: 50 words + 1 table.*

```{r b}
model1 <- lm(HEIGHT ~ DIAMETER, data = wl_wide)
summary(model1)

kable(summary(model1)$coefficients, 
      digits = 3,
      caption = "Linear regression: Height ~ Diameter")
```
We select diameter as the predictor and height as the response variable. This is reasonable since taller trees tend to have wider trunks. The model is highly statistically significant (p < 2.2e-16), with a slope of 0.109 indicating an increase in height per unit diameter. However, the low R-squared (0.15) suggests that other factors such as species and site conditions also affect tree height.

