  theme_minimal()

model_T05_sp <- lm(HEIGHT ~ DIAMETER + factor(TREE_SPEC), 
                   data = wl_wide %>% filter(SITECODE == "T05"))
model_T06_sp <- lm(HEIGHT ~ DIAMETER + factor(TREE_SPEC), 
                   data = wl_wide %>% filter(SITECODE == "T06"))
model_T08_sp <- lm(HEIGHT ~ DIAMETER + factor(TREE_SPEC), 
                   data = wl_wide %>% filter(SITECODE == "T08"))
model_T09_sp <- lm(HEIGHT ~ DIAMETER + factor(TREE_SPEC), 
                   data = wl_wide %>% filter(SITECODE == "T09"))

data.frame(
  Site = c("T05", "T06", "T08", "T09"),
  R2_without_species = c(
    summary(model_T05)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T06)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T08)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T09)$r.squared),
  R2_with_species = c(
    summary(model_T05_sp)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T06_sp)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T08_sp)$r.squared,
    summary(model_T09_sp)$r.squared)
) %>% kable(digits = 3, caption = "R-squared before and after including tree species")
```
A key feature affecting simple linear regression at all four sites is the presence of multiple tree species with distinct diameter-height relationships. Different species have different growth forms, meaning a single regression line fitted across all species will not be able to capture the true relationships within each species.
At T05, species 2600 shows a much steeper diameter-height slope than species 237, while species 441 has only a single observation, making species-level analysis unreliable for rare species. At T06, the dominant species 570 drives the overall relationship while other species show different patterns. T08 is the most species-diverse site with 30+ species, explaining its moderate R-squared of 0.38. The many different growth forms create considerable scatter around a single regression line. At T09, despite species 292 dominating, the near-zero R-squared (0.025) suggests that even within sites, species differences overwhelm any simple diameter-height relationship.
To account for this, we refit the model including TREE_SPEC as an additional categorical predictor. This substantially improves model fit across all sites. R-squared increases from 0.84 to 0.94 at T05, 0.50 to 0.69 at T06, 0.38 to 0.77 at T08, and 0.025 to 0.13 at T09. While T09 remains weak even after accounting for species, the improvements at other sites confirm that species identity is an important predictor of the diameter-height relationship.
